About
Dedicated to modern art, contemporary art, and street art, this independent museum in Amsterdam's Museumplein is a favorite amongst the youth.
Duration: 1-2 hours

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Museum Quarter (Museumkwartier)
Top sites to see in this attractive and affluent part of town include the Rijksmuseum and the Van Gogh Museum, to name but two of the highly acclaimed museums of the aptly named Museum Quarter. And if you need a break from all the fantastic art, theres the Neoclassical Concertgebouw music hall and Vondelpark, the citys largest park. Shopaholics and luxury brand connoisseurs will love exploring the high-end shopping destinations of PC Hooftstraat, Van Baerlestraat, Cornelis Schuytstraat, and Jacob Obrechtstraat, where even the shop window displays are of museum quality. In the evenings, when the museums close and the daytrippers head home, the area becomes a quiet oasis of calm with a sophisticated and urbane tone.

    Rare, Like Rocking Horse Sh#te
    Art is in the eye of the beholder, from the reviews I get it that some may not like it, but weve visited a lot of galleries- seen the headline acts and this wee museum did not disappoint. Yes some exhibits I dont understand, NFTs, but others I can certainly appreciate, I try to keep an open mind on art and try - as Public Enemy say Dont Believe The Hype. I can appreciate the artists message, their thought and the presentation within this gallery. There were some highlights, I was pleased to see, and found the descriptions provided by the gallery entirely adequate. My Higher Art (one for the Scots readers) teachers would be proud, Im sure. If youre looking for still life paintings, or fine portraiture this aint for you, but there were plenty happy faces around, plenty people taking their time to take in the art to say good on you Moco AND, oh and theres a huge rocking horse to climb up on and get a photo taken!

A lot of great art packed into a place; a lot of people packed into the same place!
Sep 2024 Family
I have to admit I was a bit dubious about this given the advertising and the schtick on the website. I was pleasantly surprised though because there is a lot packed into a small space, and there was some surprises and some great art. Robbie Williams - who'd have thunk it - was worth seeing; there was a lot of great art that came from street art and graffiti (not just Banksy); and some great Japanese artists too. The only issue was that the art was packed, and even though we were there in the morning, it was also packed, so that sometimes you had to wait about to get a chance to experience things properly. But overall I was very happy to see a lot of this work.
